{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"All prefunded ETH and extracted profits are permanently locked in the contract","locations":["FlawVerifier.sol:29","FlawVerifier.sol:61","FlawVerifier.sol:74"],"claim":"`executeOnOpportunity` relies on the contract already holding ETH so it can wrap `1 wei` into WETH, and later unwraps all harvested WETH back into raw ETH, but `FlawVerifier` exposes no withdrawal, sweep, or beneficiary-controlled transfer for either ETH or tokens.","impact":"Any ETH used to seed the strategy, any accidental ETH sent to `receive`/`fallback`, and any successful exploit proceeds become permanently irrecoverable. This can trap the operator's capital and fully strand any profits inside the contract.","paths":["An operator or third party sends ETH to the contract so `IWETH.deposit{value: 1 wei}()` can succeed","A successful run leaves value on the contract after `IWETH.withdraw(wethBal)` converts WETH into ETH","No external function exists to move ETH or ERC20 balances out of the contract"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Forced ETH donations can permanently brick `executeOnOpportunity`","locations":["FlawVerifier.sol:30","FlawVerifier.sol:66","FlawVerifier.sol:74"],"claim":"Profitability is measured against `address(this).balance` at the start of each run, so anyone can raise the required profit threshold by sending or force-sending ETH to the contract. Because the contract has no withdrawal path, the inflated baseline cannot be reset.","impact":"A griefing attacker can permanently make `executeOnOpportunity` fail once the trapped balance is high enough that the strategy cannot end with `initialBalance + 0.1 ether`. This creates a permissionless denial of service against the contract's only execution path.","paths":["An attacker transfers ETH to the contract or force-sends ETH via `SELFDESTRUCT`","`executeOnOpportunity` snapshots the donated balance in `initialBalance`","The final check `address(this).balance >= initialBalance + 0.1 ether` becomes unattainable, causing every call to revert"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Anyone can permissionlessly trigger the hardcoded exploit once the contract is funded","locations":["FlawVerifier.sol:29","FlawVerifier.sol:44","FlawVerifier.sol:51"],"claim":"`executeOnOpportunity()` is fully permissionless even though it spends the contract's prefunded ETH/WETH and irreversibly mutates the fixed target pair by syncing corrupted balances and swapping out nearly all WETH reserves. There is no owner check or designated executor.","impact":"A bot or griefing third party can front-run the intended operator, fire the exploit at an arbitrary time, and consume the one-shot opportunity through this contract. That strips the operator of execution control and can permanently leave the target pair drained while all resulting value remains trapped in the contract.","paths":["The operator funds the contract so `IWETH.deposit{value: 1 wei}()` can succeed","A third party observes the funded balance and calls `executeOnOpportunity()` first","The function syncs the manipulated reserves and drains the pair's WETH side, so later calls no longer face the same profitable state"],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Pre-existing WETH can spoof the profit check and make failed runs look successful","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"The code does count pre-existing WETH as part of the post-call ETH balance, but the practical effect is only a misleading success signal and conversion of voluntarily donated WETH into equally trapped ETH. It does not create new extractable value or a realistic protocol-level exploit beyond the already-reported trapped-funds design flaws."}]}
